  "prompt": "How does international law intersect with national laws on money laundering?",
  "response": "International law intersects with national laws on money laundering through several key mechanisms and principles:\n\n1. International Conventions and Treaties\n- UN Convention Against Transnational Organized Crime\n- Financial Action Task Force (FATF) recommendations\n- Basel Committee guidelines\n- Establish common standards and expectations for anti-money laundering (AML) efforts\n\n2. Mutual Legal Assistance\n- Countries collaborate in investigating and prosecuting money laundering cases\n- Sharing of financial intelligence and evidence across jurisdictions\n- Extradition agreements for financial criminals\n\n3. Standardized Regulatory Frameworks\n- Common reporting requirements\n- Know Your Customer (KYC) protocols\n- Customer due diligence standards\n- Suspicious transaction reporting mechanisms\n\n4. Compliance Mechanisms\n- International monitoring of national AML efforts\n- Peer review processes\n- Potential sanctions for non-compliance\n- Pressure to align national legislation with global standards\n\n5. Information Sharing Networks\n- Interpol financial crime databases\n- Egmont Group of Financial Intelligence Units\n- Cross-border communication channels\n- Real-time intelligence exchange\n\n6. Global Financial System Integration\n- Coordinated banking regulations\n- International transaction tracking\n- Unified anti-money laundering strategies\n\nThese intersections create a complex, multi-layered approach to combating financial crimes globally.",
